like that.

140
00:10:28,029 --> 00:10:29,730
I guess my acting was good.

141
00:10:30,669 --> 00:10:32,440
I think we'll get higher ratings.

142
00:10:34,809 --> 00:10:35,809
Why would you hit me?

143
00:10:35,809 --> 00:10:37,509
I'm not that swollen, right? Look.

144
00:10:45,220 --> 00:10:47,750
In order for memory to become
long-term memory,

145
00:10:47,750 --> 00:10:50,549
it needs to go through
long-term potentiation.

146
00:10:50,759 --> 00:10:52,389
However, the latter will only...

147
00:10:52,389 --> 00:10:56,090
strengthen your synapse,
and that's the problem.

148
00:10:56,360 --> 00:10:58,600
In other words, it'll select...

149
00:10:58,600 --> 00:11:00,799
already-existing memories
and delete them...

150
00:11:00,799 --> 00:11:02,730
in order to make space.

151
00:11:03,299 --> 00:11:06,899
It'll prevent the neural network
from overflowing.

152
00:11:07,440 --> 00:11:11,879
This result is also called oblivion.

153
00:11:13,840 --> 00:11:16,809
Many people think...

154
00:11:16,809 --> 00:11:19,320
that oblivion is a passive action.

155
00:11:19,519 --> 00:11:21,190
However,

156
00:11:21,419 --> 00:11:24,789
this state of oblivion
is a direct result,

157
00:11:24,789 --> 00:11:26,919
stemming from the brain,
in order to make space.

158
00:11:28,159 --> 00:11:29,629
Think about it.

159
00:11:30,460 --> 00:11:35,100
What if your brain lost
the ability to forget?

160
00:11:36,230 --> 00:11:39,639
What if it remembered everything?

161
00:11:39,639 --> 00:11:41,009
My head would explode.

162
00:11:44,340 --> 00:11:45,779
It's similar.

163
00:11:46,480 --> 00:11:48,309
It'll be overflowing.

164
00:11:48,309 --> 00:11:52,179
It'll have trouble
saving new memories.

165
00:11:52,320 --> 00:11:54,889
And even if...

166
00:11:54,889 --> 00:11:57,620
your brain could take it,

167
00:11:58,860 --> 00:12:01,830
it'd be difficult for you
to live a normal lifestyle.

168
00:12:02,759 --> 00:12:06,500
Let's say you broke up
with someone you loved.

169
00:12:07,299 --> 00:12:09,799
It'll pain you that day.

170
00:12:11,100 --> 00:12:14,039
It'll pain you for a while.

171
00:12:14,610 --> 00:12:16,340
But how would you feel
after a year...

172
00:12:17,840 --> 00:12:19,379
or 10 years?

173
00:12:21,750 --> 00:12:24,950
You may not remember their face.

174
00:12:24,950 --> 00:12:27,279
